DataElement.preferredName: Laboratory Procedure Serum Alpha-Fetoprotein Outcome Ind-2
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The yes/no indicator related to the result of procedure that involves testing of a protein normally produced by a developing fetus from the clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Information related to result of procedure that involves testing of a protein normally produced by a developing fetus from the clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A procedure for critical evaluation; a means of determining the presence, quality, or truth of something.

Concepts.definition: Any procedure that involves testing or manipulating a sample of blood, urine, or other body substance in a laboratory setting.

Property.preferredDefinition: The clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed.:Alpha-fetoprotein. A protein normally produced by a developing fetus. AFP levels are usually undetectable in the blood of healthy nonpregnant adults. An elevated level of AFP suggests the presence of either a primary liver cancer or germ cell tumor.:The result of an action.

Concepts.definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins.
Alpha-fetoprotein (609 aa, ~69 kDa) is encoded by the human AFP gene. This protein plays a role in the binding to copper, nickel, bilirubin and fatty acids in the fetal circulation.
